<CHAPTER>trayodaśamo 'dhyāyaḥ</CHAPTER> 
<TRCHAPTER>Chapter Thirteen</TRCHAPTER> 
<SUBCHAPTER>kathaṃ sukhopāyo na kriyate</SUBCHAPTER> 
<TRSUBCHAPTER>Why is the easy method not followed?</TRSUBCHAPTER> 

<TEXT> devy{ }uvāca|*</TEXT>
        <TR>Devī spoke:</TR>

<TEXT> ahiṃsātithyakānāṃ ca śruto dharmaḥ suvistaraḥ|</TEXT>
        <APP>\va <LEM>°tithya°</LEM> \msCb\msCc\msNa\Ed; °tithyā° \msCa\ \unmetr</APP>
        <NOTE>ŁPāda$s ab and cd are back-references to chapters 12 and 11,
              respectively.</NOTE>
        <TR>I have heard the Dharma of non-violence and of
            guest-reception in detail.</TR>

%folioinfo: \msNa\ 216.jpg upper
<TEXT> kiṃ na kurvanti manujāḥ sukhopāyaṃ mahatphalam||</TEXT> 13:1
        <APP>\vd <LEM>°pāyaṃ</LEM> \msCb\msCc\msNa\Ed; °<UNCL>pa</UNCL>yam \msCa</APP>
        <NOTE>Łmahatphalam$ in Łpāda$ d should be taken as a Łbahuvrīhi$ compound
              in spite of what Aṣṭādhyāyī 6.3.46 says: Łān mahataḥ samānādhikaraṇa-jātīyayoḥ$,
              `The ending of Łmahat$ becomes Łā$ (Łmahā$) before a word that should be in the same
               case (Łsamādhikaraṇa$) and before Łjātīya$'.
               Kāśikāvṛtti ad loc. adds: 
               Łamahān mahān sampanno mahadbhūtaś candramāḥ ity atra gauṇatvān mahadarthasya na bhavaty ātvam$,
               `From non-big (Łamahān$), the Moon has become big (Łmahān sampannaḥ$): 
               [this can be expressed by the phrase] Łmahadbhūtaś candramā$. 
               In this case, because of the subordinate nature of the meaning of 'Łmahat$', the
               substituion with Łā$ does not happen.'
               In the above verse in the \VSS, Łmahat$ is clearly to be taken as being
               in the same case as Łphalam$, therefore the use of Łmahat$ instead of Łmahā$ is 
               grammatically problematic. 
               See the same phenomenon mentioned in <citep>OberliesEpicSkt</citep><pnum>71</pnum>.
               Łmahatphalam$ as a Łbahuvrīhi$ appears in \SDhS\ 1.10 \CHECK and \SDhU\ 10.5,
               and Łsumahatpātaka$ as a compound in \SDHU\ 6.8 and 10. \CHECK</NOTE>
% Dominic's note on ŚDhU 10.5:
%|10.5| This interpretation requires understanding mahatphalam as a bahuvrīhi, the Pāṇinian form of which would be rather mahāphalam. Note that several South Indian sources actually read mahāphalam, whereas the Sanskit commentary reads mahatphalam but interprets it as though it were mahāphalam.
        <TR>Why do people not follow the easy method that
            brings about great rewards?</TR>

<TEXT> svaśarīre sthito yajñaḥ svaśarīre sthitaṃ tapaḥ|</TEXT>
        <APP>\va <LEM>°śarīre</LEM> \mssCaCbCc\msNa; °śarīra° \Ed</APP>
        <NOTE>ŁPāda$s ab and cd are back-references to chapters 11 and 10,
              respectively.</NOTE>
        <TR>I have heard in full detail that worship resides in one's
            own body, and penance resides in one's body,</TR>

<TEXT> svaśarīre sthitaṃ tīrthaṃ śruto vistarato mayā||</TEXT> 13:2
        <APP>\vd <LEM>vistarato</LEM> \msCa\msCc\msNa\Ed; \om\ \msCb</APP>
        <TR>and that the pilgrimage places reside in one's own body.</TR>

% note brūhi
<TEXT> kimarthaṃ bhagavan{ }brūhi sukhopāyaṃ mahatphalam|</TEXT>
        <APP>\va <LEM>°rthaṃ</LEM> \msCa\msCc\msNa\Ed; °rtha \msCb\oo
